<div id="review_2777065305" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2777065305" />
    <a title="Andy Weston" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/313206-andy-weston"><img alt="Andy Weston" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1190073185p2/313206.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2777065305?book_show_action=true">Jan 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andy Weston" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andy Weston" href="/user/show/313206-andy-weston">Andy Weston</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/313206-andy-weston?shelf=southern-gothic">southern-gothic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2777065305" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16173362822038957713">This wonderful piece of southern noir recounts the encounter, harmless enough at first, but gradually getting grimmer, between the Joe, a small-town contractor, and a desperate and deprived family of squatters. Wandering the countryside for years, scrounging and scavenging, the Jones’s take up residence in a derelict house, formerly that of the father, old man Wade, before he was driven out of town. The old man’s depravity is limitless, a dreadful figure, a serial abuser. His son Gary, wants bet</span>
  <span id="freeText16173362822038957713" style="display:none">This wonderful piece of southern noir recounts the encounter, harmless enough at first, but gradually getting grimmer, between the Joe, a small-town contractor, and a desperate and deprived family of squatters. Wandering the countryside for years, scrounging and scavenging, the Jones’s take up residence in a derelict house, formerly that of the father, old man Wade, before he was driven out of town. The old man’s depravity is limitless, a dreadful figure, a serial abuser. His son Gary, wants better, and manages to partly break the hold his father has, by working for Joe’s gang. <br />It’s a harsh story told in a tender way, a struggle for basic decency and dignity in a drained and grotesquely deformed moral landscape. <br />Brown’s signature style is his stark prose interspersed with alluring descriptions of the landscape of rural Mississippi, and a cast of surrounding characters (here, a tough but good-natured sheriff, a disabled storekeeper who collects rare books and Joe’s hardy but tender former wife) that damper down what otherwise is only bleak, give a beauty to the writing, and make the reader care. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16173362822038957713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


